Gemini: This is LIKELY because we haven't installed flask in our requirements.txt file!

BUT, before we jump to conclusions, we need to get the ls -l /app/ output from the Cloud Build logs! You haven't pasted that output yet, and it's CRUCIAL for understanding what's happening inside the Docker image.

Please go back to the Cloud Build logs URL from your last run. It was in the output of universal-deploy-script.sh and looks like this: https://console.cloud.google.com/cloud-build/builds/...

ONCE YOU ARE IN THE CLOUD BUILD LOGS PAGE:

Look for the STEP that is labeled "build" (or something similar, it's the step where Docker image is built).
Within the logs of that "build" step, SCROLL DOWN until you find the output of the command RUN ls -l /app/.
It will look like a file listing, starting with total ... and then lines with filenames like app.py, requirements.txt, updated_handler.py, etc.
COPY ONLY the ls -l /app/ output and paste it here. This is what we need to see the file structure inside your Docker image.

Example of what the ls -l /app/ output will look like in the logs (this is just an example, your output will be different):

Step #0 - "build": total 24
Step #0 - "build": -rw-r--r-- 1 root root   49 Feb 28 20:10 app.py
Step #0 - "build": -rw-r--r-- 1 root root  205 Feb 28 20:10 Dockerfile
Step #0 - "build": -rw-r--r-- 1 root root  123 Feb 28 20:10 requirements.txt
Step #0 - "build": -rw-r--r-- 1 root root 1234 Feb 28 20:10 updated_handler.py
... and so on ...
We need YOUR ls -l /app/ output to proceed! Please find it in the Cloud Build logs and paste it here. It will tell us if app.py, requirements.txt, flask (after installation), and your other Python files are in the correct place inside the Docker image.
